Title = {{Multiple Sclerosis Reduces Sensitivity to Immediate Reward During
   Decision Making}},
Journal = {{BEHAVIORAL NEUROSCIENCE}},
Year = {{2017}},
Volume = {{131}},
Number = {{4}},
Pages = {{325-336}},
Month = {{AUG}},
Abstract = {{Individuals with multiple sclerosis (MS) often face important
   health-related and financial decisions that involve trade-offs between
   short-term and long-term benefits, yet decision making is rarely studied
   in MS patients. The temporal discounting paradigm is a useful tool for
   investigating such time-dependent choices in humans. Here, we
   investigated whether patients with relapsing-remitting MS differed from
   healthy controls when making choices between hypothetical monetary
   rewards available at different points in time. Participants were tested
   in two conditions: in one, the choice was between a smaller amount of
   money available immediately and a larger amount of money available at a
   later date; in the other, a fixed delay of 60 days was added to both
   options. We found that, compared with healthy controls, MS patients
   favored less the sooner reward in the condition involving an immediate
   reward, whereas no difference between MS patients and the control group
   emerged in the condition involving only delayed rewards. Moreover, the
   decreased immediacy bias was corroborated by lower scores at scale that
   assesses responsiveness to rewards in MS patients. Taken together, these
   findings indicate reduced sensitivity to immediate reward and a
   consequent stronger willingness to defer gratification in MS
   individuals.}},
