Pages = {{519-529}},
Abstract = {{Parental reflective functioning refers to the capacity for a parent to
   understand their own and their infant's mental states, and how these
   mental states relate to behavior. Higher levels of parental reflective
   functioning may be associated with greater sensitivity to infant
   emotional signals in fostering adaptive and responsive caregiving. We
   investigated this hypothesis by examining associations between parental
   reflective functioning and neural correlates of infant face and cry
   perception using event-related potentials (ERPs) in a sample of recent
   mothers. We found both early and late ERPs were associated with
   different components of reflective functioning. These findings suggest
   that parental reflective functioning may be associated with the neural
   correlates of infant cue perception and further support the value of
   enhancing reflective functioning as a mechanism in parenting
   intervention programs.}},
